'''''New York v. Tomlins''''', 107 N.E. 496 (N.Y. 1914), is a [[criminal case]] in which it was found when a [[defendant]] claims [[self defense]], that there is no [[duty to retreat]] from one's own home. The court wrote, "It is not now and has never been the law that a man assailed in his own dwelling is bound to retreat."<ref name=CL>''Criminal Law - Cases and Materials'', 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John Kaplan (law professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora Binder]], {{ISBN|978-1-4548-0698-1}}, [https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/]</ref>{{rp|552–3}}

